Listeria monocytogenes is the etiologic agent of listeriosis, one of the major serious foodborne illnesses that occur worldwide (
Swaminathan and Gerner-Smidt, 2007; 
Huang et al., 2014). Listeriosis results in the death of 20–30% of patients, primarily in elderly people, pregnant women, children or immune-compromised populations (
Forsyth et al., 1998; 
Mead et al., 1999; 
Orsi et al., 2011). According to the European Union summary report on trends and sources of zoonoses, zoonotic agents and foodborne outbreaks (2017), there has been a significant increasing trend of confirmed listeriosis cases in the EU/EEA from 2008-to 2017 as well as during the last 5 years (period 2013–2017). In 2017, the European case fatality was 13.8% among the 1,633 confirmed cases with a known outcome, showing only a slight decrease compared to that observed in 2016.
